1
00:00:10,994 --> 00:00:15,791
Welcome back, today we're going to dive
deeper into the framework of life cycle

2
00:00:15,791 --> 00:00:17,700
impact assessment, or LCIA.

3
00:00:17,700 --> 00:00:20,265
So our learning objectives for today,

4
00:00:20,265 --> 00:00:25,719
are to describe the challenges that we
have with combining different indicators.

5
00:00:25,719 --> 00:00:29,099
And being able to compare them,
to find the key vocabulary for

6
00:00:29,099 --> 00:00:30,860
life cycle impact assessment.

7
00:00:30,860 --> 00:00:34,977
Especially focusing on this idea
of midpoint impact categories, and

8
00:00:34,977 --> 00:00:36,801
endpoint damage categories.

9
00:00:36,801 --> 00:00:41,381
And really recognize that the uncertainty
of impacts depends on interpretation

10
00:00:41,381 --> 00:00:43,545
uncertainty and model uncertainty.

11
00:00:43,545 --> 00:00:46,446
Which are often inversely related.

12
00:00:46,446 --> 00:00:51,333
So, let's say that we want to calculate
the impact of University of Michigan by

13
00:00:51,333 --> 00:00:53,194
combining some key numbers.

14
00:00:53,194 --> 00:00:58,460
Well it was founded in 1817, and
has more than 64,000 students,

15
00:00:58,460 --> 00:01:02,339
and the stadium capacity
is 106,000 students.

16
00:01:02,339 --> 00:01:07,196
Wow, these are all really big numbers so
let's get the total impact by

17
00:01:07,196 --> 00:01:11,575
just adding up all three and
we get a whopping 172,000.

18
00:01:11,575 --> 00:01:15,521
But of course in calculating this,
this doesn't make any sense,

19
00:01:15,521 --> 00:01:19,332
those numbers shouldn't be added,
even if all of them are big.

20
00:01:19,332 --> 00:01:23,671
We can't compare U of M to UCLA,
by looking at this number 170,000 and

21
00:01:23,671 --> 00:01:26,363
seeing which one's better or
more impactful.

22
00:01:26,363 --> 00:01:29,228
So but what happens is actually
in calculating impacts for

23
00:01:29,228 --> 00:01:31,457
impact assessment of different decisions.

24
00:01:31,457 --> 00:01:36,802
Many approaches end up looking for a
single final number to compare two things.

25
00:01:36,802 --> 00:01:39,685
And they end up adding things that
don't necessarily make sense.

26
00:01:39,685 --> 00:01:41,797
So in impact assessment,

27
00:01:41,797 --> 00:01:47,082
our goal is to convert things as
much to common units as possible.

28
00:01:47,082 --> 00:01:51,278
And add up those units, so
that they can be added and

29
00:01:51,278 --> 00:01:54,216
then compared to other scenarios.

30
00:01:54,216 --> 00:01:57,635
Now you've actually already seen
an example of different impact assessment

31
00:01:57,635 --> 00:01:58,272
approaches.

32
00:01:58,272 --> 00:02:02,031
When Professor Julier presented
the comparison of packaging materials.

33
00:02:02,031 --> 00:02:05,978
Where different approaches caused
different emissions to be weighted

34
00:02:05,978 --> 00:02:06,840
differently.

35
00:02:06,840 --> 00:02:10,199
He was showing you different
impact assessment methods.

36
00:02:10,199 --> 00:02:13,604
And what we can see in these
results is that even there it

37
00:02:13,604 --> 00:02:17,320
looks like different emissions
we get different results.

38
00:02:17,320 --> 00:02:21,715
We don't get the same results for
different impact assessment methods.

39
00:02:21,715 --> 00:02:25,651
And so even with a more formal
impact assessment method,

40
00:02:25,651 --> 00:02:30,580
different results can happen and
that can reveal a potential for bias.

41
00:02:30,580 --> 00:02:34,477
And this is why sometimes when such
impacts are calculated, folks might say,

42
00:02:34,477 --> 00:02:37,682
well show me your results, and
I'll just tell you who paid you.

43
00:02:37,682 --> 00:02:40,048
I'll tell you who sponsored this work,

44
00:02:40,048 --> 00:02:43,050
in order to get results
that make them look better.

45
00:02:43,050 --> 00:02:46,798
That's understandable that people are
suspicious of those results because they

46
00:02:46,798 --> 00:02:49,100
think it could be skewed
to support the sponsors.

47
00:02:49,100 --> 00:02:52,775
So to be more scientific, and
to yield more robust results,

48
00:02:52,775 --> 00:02:56,969
we need more recognized and
consistent impact assessment methods.

49
00:02:56,969 --> 00:03:02,090
Especially it turns out for toxicity
assessment, without a formal assessment,

50
00:03:02,090 --> 00:03:05,886
we all end up adding implicit and
unscientific weightings.

51
00:03:05,886 --> 00:03:09,818
So we want to be explicit with
the assumptions we're making.

52
00:03:09,818 --> 00:03:15,630
So let's say that we have the question of
how do we compare elephants and apples?

53
00:03:15,630 --> 00:03:18,059
Again it depends on your functional unit,

54
00:03:18,059 --> 00:03:21,304
like what's the thing you're
comparing them based on.

55
00:03:21,304 --> 00:03:25,365
If it's based on having to transport
them and impacts from transport,

56
00:03:25,365 --> 00:03:27,608
you care about their weight of course.

57
00:03:27,608 --> 00:03:30,740
But if you cared about the caloric intake

58
00:03:30,740 --> 00:03:35,169
which I don't like the idea
of eating an elephant at all.

59
00:03:35,169 --> 00:03:39,041
But then you would care more about the
impacts associated with getting a certain

60
00:03:39,041 --> 00:03:40,510
amount of calories out of it.

61
00:03:40,510 --> 00:03:44,328
And so, that's similar to
what we are trying to do here

62
00:03:44,328 --> 00:03:49,150
it is a difficult challenge and so
we'll dive into the details of it.

63
00:03:49,150 --> 00:03:50,885
Now in recent decades,

64
00:03:50,885 --> 00:03:55,680
international progress has been
made on LCIA, method quality.

65
00:03:55,680 --> 00:03:59,611
The first approaches did more basic
things like, group emissions and

66
00:03:59,611 --> 00:04:02,760
add emissions just based on
where they were emitted to.

67
00:04:02,760 --> 00:04:05,049
So, if I have one chemical
emitted to water and

68
00:04:05,049 --> 00:04:06,881
another chemical emitted to water.

69
00:04:06,881 --> 00:04:10,586
I can just group those because they're
both admitted to water independent of

70
00:04:10,586 --> 00:04:14,060
the ultimate impact they have,
that's called critical volumes.

71
00:04:14,060 --> 00:04:17,411
And there was another method
that what it did is it looked

72
00:04:17,411 --> 00:04:21,704
at environmental policy would define,
a critical flow of emissions.

73
00:04:21,704 --> 00:04:25,417
Like we're having a lot of this
pollutant emitted into the air or

74
00:04:25,417 --> 00:04:27,078
water, which isn't good.

75
00:04:27,078 --> 00:04:31,185
And then for a given scenario would
see how much extra was being emitted

76
00:04:31,185 --> 00:04:33,144
associated with that scenario.

77
00:04:33,144 --> 00:04:35,455
Is it close already to its critical flow?

78
00:04:35,455 --> 00:04:38,197
And so
the closer it is to its critical flow,

79
00:04:38,197 --> 00:04:42,513
the more impact it was considered
to have that's called ecopoints.

80
00:04:42,513 --> 00:04:46,271
But neither of these methods linked
to the ultimate fate exposure and

81
00:04:46,271 --> 00:04:48,031
impact of the actual emission.

82
00:04:48,031 --> 00:04:52,831
And so it turns out Leiden University in
the Netherlands played a significant role,

83
00:04:52,831 --> 00:04:56,086
in structuring the field in
terms of impact categories.

84
00:04:56,086 --> 00:04:58,517
Looking at fate exposure and impact and,

85
00:04:58,517 --> 00:05:02,690
I was lucky enough randomly to be
going to school at Leiden University.

86
00:05:02,690 --> 00:05:06,040
And meet some of the people
including Professor Hye Yoons,

87
00:05:06,040 --> 00:05:08,251
who helped come up with these methods.

88
00:05:09,910 --> 00:05:15,380
So one of the key aspects of LCIA is to
start with what we're trying to protect.

89
00:05:15,380 --> 00:05:17,800
We want to evaluate damage
to the things that we value.

90
00:05:17,800 --> 00:05:21,776
So things we want to protect our the human
system, the natural environment and

91
00:05:21,776 --> 00:05:24,358
of course life support
systems like our climate.

92
00:05:24,358 --> 00:05:28,566
And there are two different types of
values that can be considered here.

93
00:05:28,566 --> 00:05:32,924
There's the intrinsic value of we just
don't want people to get sick or die for

94
00:05:32,924 --> 00:05:33,791
human health.

95
00:05:33,791 --> 00:05:38,529
And we don't want species to go extinct,
for ecosystem quality.

96
00:05:38,529 --> 00:05:42,902
And there's also the instrumental value,
so the socioeconomic value.

97
00:05:42,902 --> 00:05:47,726
So do impacts, decrease the value
of our built infrastructure, or

98
00:05:47,726 --> 00:05:50,189
decrease the value of cash crops.

99
00:05:50,189 --> 00:05:52,212
Or in terms of natural resources,

100
00:05:52,212 --> 00:05:56,271
do our impacts decrease the amount
of minimal resources available.

101
00:05:56,271 --> 00:06:01,333
Or, the services that can be
provided by those ecosystems.

102
00:06:01,333 --> 00:06:04,145
Now of course there's also cultural value,

103
00:06:04,145 --> 00:06:08,893
such as valuing the cultural heritage
of historic buildings or monuments.

104
00:06:08,893 --> 00:06:13,122
Or value of the natural heritage or
flora, fauna and geology.

105
00:06:13,122 --> 00:06:18,154
And at the moment LCIA hasn't
really delved into that realm,

106
00:06:18,154 --> 00:06:20,491
but I hope that it does soon.

107
00:06:20,491 --> 00:06:25,189
And so the way that we look at
the damage to these areas of protection,

108
00:06:25,189 --> 00:06:28,111
is described somewhat in ISO 14044.

109
00:06:28,111 --> 00:06:32,919
Which describes an impact
category that we can use an LCIA.

110
00:06:32,919 --> 00:06:36,635
Which means we take our life
cycle inventory results,

111
00:06:36,635 --> 00:06:40,851
and we assign these results to
different impact categories.

112
00:06:40,851 --> 00:06:45,390
And we use impact modeling to compare the
midpoint damage, at different categories.

113
00:06:45,390 --> 00:06:48,730
We can then use damage modeling or
qualitative approaches,

114
00:06:48,730 --> 00:06:50,635
to compare this midpoint damage.

115
00:06:50,635 --> 00:06:54,229
To ultimately a damage to one
of our areas of protection.

116
00:06:54,229 --> 00:06:59,027
That's the overview, so
let's dive a little bit deeper into that.

117
00:06:59,027 --> 00:07:03,876
The UNEP-SETAC framework, describes
this midpoint and damage, framework.

118
00:07:03,876 --> 00:07:08,752
So we have our emissions to air water or
soil and resource extractions,

119
00:07:08,752 --> 00:07:13,642
and these can each be linked to
different midpoint impact categories.

120
00:07:13,642 --> 00:07:18,549
So for example emission of CFCs,
can be linked both to ozone depletion and

121
00:07:18,549 --> 00:07:21,964
to climate change because
it's a greenhouse gas.

122
00:07:21,964 --> 00:07:26,951
These midpoint impacts can then be
grouped together to look at their damage,

123
00:07:26,951 --> 00:07:28,573
their endpoint damage.

124
00:07:28,573 --> 00:07:33,543
For example to human health,
ecosystem quality, natural resources.

125
00:07:33,543 --> 00:07:38,394
And again, a given midpoint impact it's
okay for it to be added up together,

126
00:07:38,394 --> 00:07:41,247
to connect to different damage categories.

127
00:07:41,247 --> 00:07:45,416
So ozone depletion and climate
change can affect human health, but

128
00:07:45,416 --> 00:07:48,644
climate change can also
affect ecosystem quality.

129
00:07:48,644 --> 00:07:50,264
Now in this framework,

130
00:07:50,264 --> 00:07:55,859
it is allowed to then combine the damage
categories into a single weighted score.

131
00:07:55,859 --> 00:07:59,176
Because people often want to
compare an array of scenarios.

132
00:07:59,176 --> 00:08:02,420
And they just want to get a final
score for each scenario and

133
00:08:02,420 --> 00:08:03,918
see which one looks best.

134
00:08:03,918 --> 00:08:06,843
But that does get a little
bit like are UFM example,

135
00:08:06,843 --> 00:08:10,665
where you're then adding things
that don't have similar units.

136
00:08:10,665 --> 00:08:14,391
And have to apply your own weighting and
your own biases of what you value most.

137
00:08:14,391 --> 00:08:18,704
And so, we usually wouldn't take it to
the next level of a weighted score.